men negotiate the rhetorics of translation and gift-culture in order to articulate political and religious affiliations and beliefs in their carefully crafted manuscript gift-books. This book offers a critical lens through which to read early modern translations in relation to the materiality of early modern gift culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthorshipxPolitical aspectszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aAuthorshipxPolitical aspectszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aEnglish literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aTranslating and interpretingzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aTranslating and interpretingzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aTranslation (history), Renaissance women writers, gift-giving (history), early modern political culture, material culture, manuscript circulation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311102374840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048542963?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048542963423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789048542963/original  a978-3-11-102374-8  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles